&gt;About two weeks ago, my car hit the rear bumper of another Honda car
&gt;in front in another city when he stops suddenly, because of another
&gt;car in front of him stopped suddenly.

&gt;1) Am I the only one at fault and need to pay his damage, getting to
&gt;close, although he stopped suddenly?

"/> Yes. If you hadn't been following too closely, you would have been
able to stop without hitting him. You're lucky an officer didn't give
you a ticket for &quot;Assured Clear Distance&quot;.

The fact that the other car stopped quickly is irrelevant. Cars do
stop in traffic; a driver has a legal obligation to leave enough room
ahead that he can stop without hitting the vehicle ahead.

You should have reported this to your insurance company. (Hopefully
it is not too late to do that.) Insurance companies don't just pay
whatever estimate the other driver gives; they try to keep payouts
low. It's even possible that the payout might be too little to
trigger a premium increase, though I wouldn't hold out much hope.

