"/> Yes. The assumption in most states is the rearender is at fault and it
is up to you to prove that you could not avoid hitting the other car
despite taking reasonable precautions. This usually requires something
extraordinary like you hit black ice, skidded out of your lane and
rearended the car in the next lane.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;2) Can he just show one repair estimate (which may be the highest in
&gt;all estimates), instead of say three repair estimates (for the lowest)
&gt;which he agreed first at first and then decided not to get more
&gt;estimates?

"/> Yes. It is probably his way of getting the maximum money from you and
in theory you can fight it by requiring multiple bids. However as a
practical matter he has you over the barrel. See 4) and 5).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;3) He wants me to write him a cheque of $400 payable to him
&gt;personally. Do I have to pay him personally, instead of paying to the
&gt;Honda dealer repair shop? I suspect that, based on the slight
&gt;scratches/dents, he might just pocket the money himself without
&gt;getting the bumper repaired.

"/> Yes. I have had insurance companies ask me if I wanted to repair the
car or do I want them to just make out the check to me. This is when
the other guy was at fault and it was his company paying for the
repairs. Basically he can chose to just pocket the money if he want to
just as I was allowed to pocket the money if I wanted to.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;4) Can he insist on me paying for $400 for the whole bumper repaired?
&gt;If he goes to his insurance company, is my insurance company required
&gt;to pay $400?

"/> If this goes to your insurance company, your company pays for
everything. However your company is in a better position than you to
force him to be reasonable. They can require multiple bids and pay
only the smallest amount. They can say they will only pay the amount
that their adjustor says is valid. Etc. So there is a certain
incentive for the guy to avoid going to your insurance company but you
have more to lose if he does that. See 5).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;5) If my insurance company is involved, do I (customer) generally have
&gt;an option paying for the damage, and thus (I hope) would not increase
&gt;my insurance premium in the future?

"/> Generally speaking no. Just reporting it creates a black mark on your
record that will last about 5 years. It will probably cause an
increase in your rates for those 5 years. That extra money may be more
than $400 over the 5 years or it could be less. Too many black marks
can be cause for cancellation. You have to decide whether it is worth
it or not to pay the $400 yourself and keep the incident off the
books.

Danny

